Here's an example of generating an automatic table of contents (TOC) in a LATEX document using the standard `\tableofcontents` command with the help of the `titletoc` package:

```latex
\documentclass{book}
\usepackage{titletoc} % Required for customizing TOC

% Define TOC style and formatting
\titlecontents{chapter}
  [0em] % Left indent
  {\bfseries\large} % Chapter font style
  {\thecontentslabel\space} % Chapter label (e.g. "Chapter")
  {\hspace{1em}} % Space between label and title
  {\MakeUppercase{#2}} % Title in uppercase
  [\hfill\titlepagenumber\hfill] % Page number in right column

\begin{document}

% Chapter/Section/Subsection headings
\chapter{Introduction}
\section{Background}
\subsection{History}
\subsection{Current State of Affairs}

% Automatic Table of Contents generation
\tableofcontents % Generates TOC based on headings

% Chapter content
\chapter{Methodology}
\section{Data Collection}
\subsection{Survey Design}
\subsubsection{Questionnaire Development}

% (rest of document content)

\end{document}
```

When you run the above code, it will generate a table of contents automatically (based on chapter, section, and subsection headings) with custom formatting as per the `\titlecontents` command. The final document will contain a beautifully formatted table of contents with page numbers, headings, and subheadings listed in the desired order.

