In Java, the `==` operator compares object references for equality, checking if two object instances point to the same location in memory. This is not suitable for comparing string values (i.e., their content) as strings in Java are immutable objects (i.e., their values cannot be modified once created).

On the other hand, `.equals()` is the appropriate method to compare string values for equality. It compares the content of the two strings character by character and returns `true` if they have the same content, and `false` otherwise.

Here's a summary of when to use `==` vs. `.equals()` when comparing strings in Java:

| Operator/Method | Purpose | Example |
| --- | --- | --- |
| `==` | Compares object references for equality | **Wrong** for comparing strings: `if (str1 == str2) {... }`
| `.equals()` | Compares string values for equality | **Correct** for comparing strings: `if (str1.equals(str2)) {... }`

Here's why `==` is not suitable for comparing strings:

- `==` checks if two string variables are pointing to the same object in memory. For instance, consider the following code:
```java
String str1 = "hello";
String str2 = "hello";
if (str1 == str2) { // false, even though str1 and str2 have the same content
  System.out.println("Strings are equal");
}
```
Here, `str1` and `str2` are two different string objects created at different memory locations, even though they have the same value.

- `==` also returns `false` for strings that have different content, but were created at the same memory location (e.g., by assigning one string variable to another):
```java
String str1 = "abc";
String str2 = str1;
if (str1 == str2) { // false, even though str1 and str2 reference the same object
  System.out.println("Strings are equal");
}
```

On the other hand, using `.equals()` solves these issues and correctly compares string values:
```java
String str1 = "hello";
String str2 = "hello";
if (str1.equals(str2)) { // true, strings have identical content
  System.out.println("Strings are equal");
}
```

In summary, always use the `.equals()` method to compare string values in Java, and avoid using the `==` operator, as it only checks object references, which can lead to bugs and errors, especially when working with immutable objects like strings.

Here is a non-loop/recursive Java solution to check if an integer `n` is a power of three:

```java
public class PowerOfThreeChecker {

    /**
     * Checks if a given integer n is a power of three.
     *
     * @param n integer to check
     * @return true if n is a power of three, false otherwise
     */
    public static boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
        // Special cases
        if (n <= 0) return false;
        if (n == 1) return true;

        // Check if n is a power of 3 by taking logarithm
        double log = Math.log(n) / Math.log(3);
        return Double.valueOf(log).isInteger() && n == (int) Math.pow(3, (int) log);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThree(27)); // true
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThree(0)); // false
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThree(-1)); // false
    }
}
```

Explanation:

- We first check for special cases (0 and negative numbers cannot be powers of three).
- Then, we use the property of logarithms to check if `n` is a power of 3. Specifically, if `log3(n)` (i.e., the exponent such that 3 raised to that power equals `n`) is an integer, then `n` is a power of 3. 
- We take the logarithm of `n` with base 3 and divide it by logarithm of 3 (which is approximately 1/ ln(3) ~ 0.4771212547... ), and check if the result is an integer and if `n` equals `3` raised to that integer power.
- We use `Double.valueOf(log).isInteger()` to check if `log` is an integer, and `Math.pow(3, (int) log) == n` to check if `n` is equal to 3 raised to that integer power. 

This solution has a time complexity of O(1) and space complexity of O(1), which is optimal.

The hexadecimal (#) and RGB (rgb()) CSS code for a light red color with a medium-light shade of pink (pinky-red hue) are:

**Hexadecimal Code:**
```css
# Light Red with Medium-light Shade of Pink (hex): #EF9A9C
```

**RGB Code:**
```css
# Light Red with Medium-light Shade of Pink (rgb()): rgba(239, 154, 156, 1) (opaque, with alpha=1)
```

(Alternatively, you can adjust the hue, saturation, and lightness values for a custom Pinkish-Red tone using HSL/HEX-A color model)

```css
/* Using HSL (hue-based color model) */
# Light Red with Medium-light Shade of Pink (hsl): hsl(345deg 58% 87%);

/* Example CSS for use: */

/* Hex Code */
.element {
  background-color: #EF9A9C;
  color: #fff; /* Contrast with white text */
}

/* RGB Code */
.element {
  background-color: rgba(239, 154, 156, 1);
  color: #fff; /* Contrast with white text */
}

/* HSL Code (for customized hue, saturation, lightness values) */
.element {
  background-color: hsl(345deg 58% 87%);
  color: #fff; /* Contrast with white text */
}
```

Example usage in HTML:

```html
<div class="element" style="width: 200px; height: 200px;">
  <p>Text in light red with medium-light shade of pink</p>
</div>
```

Output:

```html
<div class="element" style="width: 200px; height: 200px; background-color: #EF9A9C; color: #fff;">
  <p style="color: #fff;">Text in light red with medium-light shade of pink</p>
</div>
```

(Note: You can adjust the opacity/alpha value by using `rgba()` with a fourth value between 0 (transparent) and 1 (opaque).)

